<br>
For those fantasy fans(not everyone is big on fantasy yet they play EQ), Gandalf went toe to toe with the balrog in Moria.  Some wizards follow this image, some follow the image of a skinny weakling who throws huge damage spells from far away.  If you can play it where you get agro without getting too badly hurt(needing a LOT of cleric mana), then go for it.  If you can't cut it toe to toe with a mob, then don't play that way.<br>
<br>
Now, it's clear that all of us need to approach named mobs differently than the normal mobs we fight in XP groups because they hit harder.  Those who push the agro line DO tend to step back a bit on named, especially when the named mobs don't die quickly.  But that's also a part of the art of playing a wizard.<br>
<br>
So, if you feel that wizards should NEVER get agro, or should never take ANY damage, that's your right, you play the class the way you will.  Others who enjoy riding the edge of agro also have the right, as long as they know by the time they hit the high level game how to play it.<br>
<br>
If you have two wizards who are agressive, and know to stay in melee range when in an XP group, they can be a VERY solid team while allowing the melees to contribute fully.  Nothing wrong with it, and any clerics who deny that wizards CAN do a very good level of damage when working together doesn't have much experience with us.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 65 Wizard<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
